commentBody:
@Marshall Walthew

I agree wholeheartedly with your take on this delightful puzzle. Have also lived in our home for over 30 years and established many overflowing   cottage-y flower beds, which stand proudly aside the monocultures assiduously maintained by too many neighbors. CROSS-POLLINATors are welcome here!

This spring I’m mostly sidelined as I rehab from shoulder surgery, so your ending comment resonated with me. Enjoy every minute of gardening this season and many more!

@Alex

I think there's a critical mass of entries that you either have to know or make a good guess on before a puzzle will fall into place.

My experiences with the older puzzles is that I can't find any gimmes or near-gimmes that cross or align--just a bunch of letters out there in the puzzle I can't use

@SBK in TO

I truly do appreciate the gift of a cryptic, but I'm afraid I'm completely ignorant about them.  

But just because you went out of your way to send me this, I'm going to learn how cryptics work and figure it out!

@lucky13
As exemplified by the Lotus Elan: <a href="https://www.lotuscars.com/fr-FR/lotus-story/road-cars/elan" target="_blank">https://www.lotuscars.com/fr-FR/lotus-story/road-cars/elan</a>

My dad had a 1969 Elan. Surprisingly he let me learn to drive on it. What a great car! So fun to drive, especially with the top down.

@Bob T. 
@lucky13

My family moved out to the suburbs of Boston when I was in 2nd grade. There were two small peony plants in the little garden in front of the barn – pretty much every item in that sentence was so foreign to this city kid! – and I found the flowers horrifyingly disgusting due to the ants that would crawl all over the stems and buds. 

Flash forward 50 years, and the peonies are some of my favorite blooms! Last year their full blossoming coincided with the tail end of the cherries, which made that corner of the Brooklyn Botanic Garden an eruption of pink petals. But a few weeks ago at the BBG, the peonies didn't even have buds! Hopefully this cold Spring won't keep them away much longer.

@Dena R. Verkuil

I thought you'd never ask... :-)
"Climb Every Mountain."

@sotto voce
Deeply disagreeing with you. I find that song draggy, overperformed (both in the hamming it up sense, and in the hearing it too often sense), with pedestrian (hah!) lyrics. If you find it inspiring, may you continue to do so. 
Me, I'll take 'When You Walk Through a Storm' from Carousel. Clearly better musically and less exhausting to listen to.

@lucky13
I differentiate between ALTHEA (Rose of Sharon) and HIBISCUS, although they are related.  
(Neither is appropriate for use in a LEI.)

@Francis

I love nature - being surrounded by trees, flowers, and any sort of plant, really, calms me and actually makes me feel happy. When my mother died, my father and I let the garden she had kept neat and orderly at our family home return to its natural state. We both love the wild riot of color it has become, and how animals and insects returned to a space previously designed for humans only. I also have quite the collection of cacti and succulents on the bay window sill of my and my wife's condo. Yet I'm hopeless with plant- and flower-related terminology.

And don't get me started on fish. I can name some in Polish, and identify a few of them, but in English I feel completely lost. Same with birds. All those terns, wrens, chars, gars and the like that keep popping up in NYT puzzles only exist in my head as names with no real-world associations.

@Matt

I also had a very brief and particularly abortive experience with scouting. As soon as it became obvious discipline and following orders were involved, I was outta there :D

@Andrzej

You should consider writing everything in Greek and letting those of us interested translate it on our own.

That would certainly outsmart the large, flightless birds.

@Mean Old Lady
@Francis
A. The answer to "Can I say this here?" should almost always be yes. 
B. Not being able to name things does not necessarily reflect one's emotional connection or lack thereof. I love flowers but am hard put to recognize them without those little sticks with the name tags on them. Similarly, I love the stars but can barely recognise the Big Dipper. I still recognize the beauty of a field of wildflowers or the night sky.
C. It's not from want of effort. I've read plenty of science and nature materials, gone for long walks in Toronto's beautiful ravines, and been given plenty of plants and bouquets. Still, I couldn't describe a dahlia at gunpoint. Sigh.

@Mike

You bee you. Mike!
Always causing a buzz in the column-y.

@Mike
I'm rooting for you!
(Can't believe no one used this already!)

@Ned S

Nope.

He was born in Ockham but his name was Latinized to "Occam."

@Gunbir

That's not fair. I didn't enjoy the puzzle much, personally, as being Polish I found the themed clues ungettable, but I can appreciate it was well costructed. Designing a doable grid with four pairs of crossing flower names must have been very hard.

I critize puzzle construction, myself, occasionally - for example, when naticks are involved (two proper names crossing with no obvious choice of letter at the crossing if you don't know both entries) - but never as you did today, very harshly and with no justification.

@Bill

I'm glad to have bumped into you here. I look forward to hearing the Bolcom rag — I've loved Scott Joplin's music ever since its anachronistic use for the soundtrack of "The Sting." 

And one of my favorite memories of a serendipitous moment was a visit to the St. Louis Museum of Art on a rainy afternoon in the late 1980s. I was with my husband and three (maybe four?) of my six siblings. We turned a corner and were confronted by a brass quartet or quintet playing ragtime music. It was delightful to listen to for a bit.

@Bill

Thanks!

I’m fine. Just busy with other stuff.

@Grant
So, that makes two of us....

It IS lonely at the top, eh?

@The X-Phile
Well, that has just re-set my mood for the morning!  I am grateful.

I was able to get in touch with a math prof at Florida Southern College who had literally cured my Math Phobia...  In the intervening years he had gone on to complete a PhD and return to teaching at FSC, while I had gone on to help many sufferers who hated and feared "The Queen of Sciences" (as he termed it.)  Dr. Hartje is still a Hero in my Pantheon.

@Marc A. Leaf
I join you in congratulating our new constructor.
He's not likely to have written that ignorant, ridiculous, appalling clue.  Or so we hope.

@Charles Nelson Reilly
Nope.  
You didn't learn anything.  None of those flowers/plants CROSS POLLINATE, not being sufficiently related...unless someone has come up with an idle AI drawing or bogus claim.  The only thing they got right was the role that BEES play (along with other insects, from ants to wasps.  And I have been known to help out, as well.  A cheap watercolor brush is perfect for the job.)

@The X-Phile

There are definitely two different types of HIBISCUS. One is the tropical one. The other is the one grown here. It is also called Rose of Sharon (and lots of other names). I removed all my Rose of Sharon recently. They had reached to the second floor of my home. But they made little Rose of Sharon weeds all over the yard. Little woody treelets that are hard to remove.  Now my neighbor's Rose of Sharon colonizes my yard only. I don't recommend this plant although you might try to grow it in a container.

It's also true that these flowers are very short-lived once picked.

@Cyndie
Fake products on Amazon?
That’s just fake news😋

@The X-Phile
I am from Hawaii. Never in my life have I seen a lei made out of hibiscus. 

A margarita? Sure. A lei? Nope. 🤙

